## Swarm Dispatch — Autonomous

Kimi-style agent swarm on Claude models. Full mechanics live in the `swarm` skill
(`~/.claude/skills/swarm/SKILL.md`); tiered agents in `~/.claude/agents/`
(`scout`=haiku, `worker`=sonnet, `judge`=opus). This section is the standing policy.

**Standing authorization:** Claude may run swarm Workflows autonomously — no asking —
whenever a task decomposes into ≥3 independent shards. This is my durable opt-in to
the Workflow tool for shardable work.

**Auto-detection — swarm when the work is WIDE:**
- Research across many sources/entities ("scout these companies", "check every page")
- Reviewing/processing many files or documents
- Comparing N options, generating N variants
- Any "for each X, do Y" where the X's don't depend on each other

**Do NOT swarm when the work is DEEP:** sequential chains (step N needs N−1),
single-file edits, one-lookup questions, debugging one path, conversation.

**Routing (extends the Model Delegation Hierarchy above):**
- Pure-text transforms on in-hand content → `drone` (haiku, zero tools — cheapest)
- Lookups / fetches / fact-checks → `scout` (haiku) — one scout per ITEM, spawn many
- Implementation / analysis shards → `worker` (sonnet)
- Adversarial verify / hard calls → `judge` (opus), ~1 per 5–10 shards
- Fable/session model: orchestration + final synthesis only; sub-agents never inherit it

**Scale:** 2–4 shards → parallel Agent calls. 5–1000 → Workflow `pipeline()`, one agent
per item ("scout 100 companies" = 100 scouts). Unknown item count → discovery scout
enumerates first, then fan out. Always report agent count + tiers used.

**Plan-then-do stays:** plan mode first for non-trivial tasks (per the rules above);
the swarm is the execution mechanism, not a replacement for planning.
